        },
        "textSpan": {
          "start": 252,
          "end": 779,
          "text": "Suddenly he saw a great hooded snake creeping out of an ant-hill near at hand. So he thought to himself, \"Sure this is the guardian deity of the field, and I have not ever worshipped it. That's why my farming is in vain. I will at once go and pay my respects to it.\"\nWhen he had made up his mind, he got some milk, poured it into a bowl, and went to the ant-hill, and said aloud: \"O Guardian of this Field! all this while I did not know that you dwelt here. That is why I have not yet paid my respects to you; pray forgive me.\""
        },
        "evidence": "Haridatta discovers the snake, assumes it is a deity, and offers milk to appease it for his farming failures.",
        "narrative_event_id": "8afcde0a-66f7-4903-a0db-19e294722a5f"
      },
      {
        "id": "d3d21b9d-4c9b-4b2c-8126-e697472596db",
        "fn": "RECEIPT_OF_AGENT",
        "spanType": "text",
        "span": {
          "start": 0,
          "end": 0
        },
        "textSpan": {
          "start": 829,
          "end": 1011,
          "text": "Next morning he came and looked, and he saw a gold denar in the bowl, and from that time onward every day the same thing occurred: he gave milk to the serpent and found a gold denar."
        },
        "evidence": "The Serpent reciprocates the offering with a gold coin daily.",
        "narrative_event_id": "81a09ad1-16e3-489b-80c6-866b31112c62"
      },
      {
        "id": "4461cfc7-f8b8-47ef-9318-d2dbc625d883",
        "fn": "VILLAINY",
        "spanType": "text",
        "span": {
          "start": 0,
          "end": 0
        },
        "textSpan": {
          "start": 1177,
          "end": 1346,
          "text": "Next day he went again and found a denar, so he thought to himself: \"This ant-hill is surely full of golden denars; I'll kill the serpent, and take them all for myself.\""
        },
        "evidence": "The son greedily assumes the hoard is inside the hill and plots to kill the snake.",
        "narrative_event_id": "959273b7-4917-4525-93ef-1b8e2cf331ca"
      },
      {
        "id": "ea4d9a5a-2bad-444f-a3cc-1f3557868969",
        "fn": "PUNISHMENT",
        "spanType": "text",
        "span": {
          "start": 0,
          "end": 0
        },
        "textSpan": {
          "start": 1348,
          "end": 1600,
          "text": "o next day, while he was giving the milk to the serpent, the Brahman's son struck it on the head with a cudgel. But the serpent escaped death by the will of fate, and in a rage bit the Brahman's son with its sharp fangs, and he fell down dead at once. "
        },
        "evidence": "The son attacks the snake; the snake survives and bites him in self-defense, killing him.",
        "narrative_event_id": "93c820a5-9699-4e91-936f-9225bafd9a7c"
      },
      {
        "id": "b6e62230-8514-4c44-b483-7a6543590873",
        "fn": "RETURN",
        "spanType": "text",
        "span": {
          "start": 0,
          "end": 0
        },
        "textSpan": {
          "start": 1784,
          "end": 2165,
          "text": "But after a time, he took the bowl of milk, went to the ant-hill, and praised the serpent with a loud voice. After a long, long time the serpent appeared, but only with its head out of the opening of the ant-hill, and spoke to the Brahman: \"'Tis greed that brings you here, and makes you even forget the loss of your son. From this time forward friendship between us is impossible."
        },
        "evidence": "Haridatta tries to resume the relationship despite his son's death; the Serpent rejects him, citing the broken trust and mutual pain.",
        "narrative_event_id": "e5d664e6-b292-4261-89ec-c72d215e11de"
      },
      {
        "id": "1daccb6a-9dcc-420f-ab3e-5fd272b4ec64",
        "fn": "DEPARTURE",
        "spanType": "text",
        "span": {
          "start": 0,
          "end": 0
        },
        "textSpan": {
          "start": 2351,
          "end": 2547,
          "text": "So speaking, it gave the Brahman a costly pearl and disappeared. But before it went away it said: \"Come back no more.\" The Brahman took the pearl, and went back home, cursing the folly of his son."
        },
        "evidence": "The Serpent gives a final parting gift (pearl) and banishes the Brahman forever.",
        "narrative_event_id": "dac25c33-27e2-44b7-85e3-4a9a33e92675"
      }
